🧠 Project Title: MNIST Digit Recognition
📚 Overview
The MNIST Digit Recognition project is a deep learning-based image classification task designed to identify handwritten digits ranging from 0 to 9. It utilizes the MNIST dataset, which contains 70,000 grayscale images of size 28x28 pixels, divided into 60,000 training and 10,000 testing samples. This project showcases how machine learning, specifically neural networks, can be applied to visual data for high-accuracy classification.

⚙️ Workflow Summary
The project begins by importing essential Python libraries such as NumPy, Matplotlib, TensorFlow/Keras, and Scikit-learn. The dataset is then loaded, reshaped, and normalized to improve performance and ensure efficient training. A Sequential deep learning model is constructed using either Dense (fully connected) or Convolutional layers (CNNs), followed by compilation with the Adam optimizer and categorical cross-entropy loss.

🚀 Model Training & Evaluation
The model is trained over several epochs, with real-time feedback on training and validation performance. After training, the model's accuracy is evaluated on the test set, typically achieving over 98% accuracy. To better understand its performance, the notebook visualizes prediction results, plots a confusion matrix heatmap, and displays sample misclassifications.

📊 Results & Insights
The model successfully demonstrates high precision in recognizing digits, making it a strong baseline for image classification problems. Its architecture, performance, and analysis highlight the strength of deep learning in pattern recognition tasks.

🎓 Educational Value
This notebook provides a complete learning pipeline — from data preprocessing and model building to evaluation and visualization — making it an excellent educational example for beginners in computer vision and deep learning.
